    {
      "id": "b95a0c829434bdda7825240f96e42a58dfbf37c1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-12 21:32:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\nSeems OK in general, but I don't know much about the CLIO part of the code.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9513ffeffe4339a6ba80040b7e93639c803bf064",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-12 23:13:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nActually I don't understand the purpose of this patch. It seems LPROC_LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} should do stats for how many bytes/pages from applications.\n\nIf you'd really like to know the exact bytes transfered over network, can you please take a look at ptlrpc_lprocfs_brw() which is called in osc_send_oap_rpc() to collect how many bytes prepare for transfer.\n\nI noticed that LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} is actually not used by llite and liblustre, I'll appreciate if you can bring it back.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c94538eea00a5640dd373d6054422b178f2fa4f3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-13 21:59:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Actually I don't understand the purpose of this patch. It seems\n> LPROC_LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} should do stats for how many bytes/pages\n> from applications.\n\nI guess I'm not clear on what LPROC_LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} were\noriginally supposed to represent.  Outside of lloop, in 1.6 and 1.8\nLPROC_LL_BRW_WRITE is not used, and LPROC_LL_BRW_READ was only used to\nread a partial page in ll_prepare_write().\n\n> If you'd really like to know the exact bytes transfered over\n> network, can you please take a look at ptlrpc_lprocfs_brw() which is\n> called in osc_send_oap_rpc() to collect how many bytes prepare for\n> transfer.\n\nAs a consumer of these stats, I have two issues here.  First, the OSC\nBRW stats represent the number of bytes requested.  It's much better\nto tally by the number of bytes actually transferred.  Since this way\nwe don't have to wonder if the user is triggering an error (like over\nquota of something) or is really doing a large amount of IO.\n\nSecond, I really want four numbers here: cumulative byte and request\ncounts for reads and writes.  To use the OSC BRW stats for this\npurpose on TACC's largest lustre filesystem, I need to read 300\n(#OSTs) files.  If I use stdio that means 1800 system calls.  Reading\none stats file takes 0.000080 seconds, reading 300 takes 0.037.\n\n> I noticed that LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} is actually not used by llite and\n> liblustre, I'll appreciate if you can bring it back.\n\nOK, but I'm not sure exactly what to tally.\n\nWould you ACK this if I replace LPROC_LL_BRW_{READ,WRITE} with two new\ncounters?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "953432534b77fe63d6fd6df06d1498a08d2f622d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-14 18:46:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nQUOTE \"As a consumer of these stats, I have two issues here. First, the OSC BRW stats represent the number of bytes requested. It's much better to tally by the number of bytes actually transferred. Since this way we don't have to wonder if the user is triggering an error (like over quota of something) or is really doing a large amount of IO.\"\n\nIndeed, what I meant is to add two new counters for this purpose, for example, let's say(see definition of BRW_READ_BYTES): \n   BRW_TRANS_READ_BYTES\n   BRW_TRANS_WRITE_BYTES\n\nand implement a similar function as ptlrpc_lprocfs_brw() which will operate the above two counters, for example, let's name it as:\n   ptlrpc_lprocfs_brw_trans()\n\nand then call this function in brw_interpret().\n\nI think it's clearer in this way. How do you think?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
